Author: University of Minnesota PreCalculus Dept.
Reviewed/Remixed by: Doenet team

About the problem: Determine how many sequences of heads and tails have a certain number of heads. Application of the standard formula for combinations.
This problem is randomized with the number of total coin flips ranging from 4 to 10, and required number of heads ranging from 2 to 6.
The Worked Example can be hidden by commenting out the <hint> portion of the document.
*************************************************************-->

<problem>
<setup>
  <selectFromSequence name="k" from="2" to="6" type="math"/>
  <selectFromSequence name="b" from="2" to="4"/>
  <math name="n" simplify>$k + $b</math>
  <math name="combinationskOfN" simplify>$n!/($k!($n - $k)!)</math>
</setup>


<!--testing--> 
<!-- <p>k = $k</p>
<p>b = $b</p>
<p>n = $n</p>
<p>combinationskOfN = $combinationskOfN</p> -->
<!--testing-->

<p>When flipping $n coins, how many sequences of Heads and Tails have exactly $k Heads?</p>  

  <p><m>\text{Number of sequences} = </m>
      
    <answer name="ans2" >
      <mathInput name="userInput"/> 
      <award name="correct" symbolicEquality simplifyOnCompare credit="1">    
        <when>
      $userInput=$combinationskOfN
        </when>
      </award>
    </answer>
  </p>

